The faceless one had foreseen the end of the world perfectly again.

A gold instrument studded with blue crystals whirred in his ivory hand. Below the balcony, a plaza teemed with people. They screamed. They struggled. It made no difference. The floating towers of light overhead shuddered and fell. The instrument slowed. It stilled.

Mountains melted. Sound ended the moment it began. The screams halted mid-breath. The sun shifted from gold to bruised purple and went out.

The faceless one tilted his head and calculated the interval before his next revival. He always returned.

As always, he watched reality fold. He raised a hand, but let it fall. Intercessions were useless. White light shone through widening cracks in the earth. Stone peeled back. Sea withdrew. The world thinned to brightness.

Then even that was gone.

--

On the morning of the mining disaster, the highest peak of the Blackvein mountains pierced the pale sun. At the black base of the mountain, Coalridge bustled under a layer of coal dust. Mine carts trundled, wagon wheels groaned, mules brayed, and the morning seeped into the overshadowed town with the color of pink, watery blood. 

It happened without warning. No creaks. No tremors. Just ground thunder that shook the mountains to the roots and reverberated through the bones of every living soul. Dust gushed out of the mouth of the Coalridge Pit and blinded everyone in a black, suffocating fog. Every ear rang. Then silence. People clawed their way back to the Pit to see what happened, to find anyone who still lived.

Matthis remembered that day over a year ago. The running, the shouts, the crying. The blood. Blood-soaked coal dust was the blackest of blacks he had ever seen. The cave-in claimed twenty-two souls, including five wizards. He remembered the argument in the village square, the lit torches that whipped angry shadows along the cobbled ground and raked the buildings. He remembered the weeping women, the children who smeared their faces in their mothers' soot-blackened aprons.

The bars of the new iron gibbet sucked the warmth from his hand. It had been over a year, he reminded himself, since that happened. Over a year since the tunnel collapse. In some ways, the cave in had destroyed more than just a tunnel. He tipped the contraption onto its side and rolled it through the village square. It made hollow bong-gong noises from the bars and shallow rattles from the hinges. He stopped to catch his breath in the center of the square. Miners who emerged from their hostels with tools slung in bags over their shoulders watched him. His breath came heavy. His body burned from exertion. 

The looks in the miners' eyes as they passed held a mixture of disgust and respect. Although they avoided eye contact, they walked more slowly as they neared him, and then picked up the pace after they passed. A salute and a snub all at once. No one wanted Matthis' work. Terrible. Reprehensible. But necessary.

Matthis rolled the gibbet to the edge of the village. The gallows rose with every step. The Death Guild was a squat stone building that reeked of metal, decay, blood, and ash. Iron gibbets hung at intervals along the gallows. The gibbet chains clanked together. The yellow, bare bones of the year-old, undead wizard skeletons clacked. One of the iron collar rings, still fastened around a bony neck, slipped off the skeleton's collar bone and chinked against the bars. The undead swayed with the wind.

A small group had gathered near the gallows, which was less a gallows and more like a single beam supported by sturdy mining timber. Each person wore the expression of someone about to face a battle. Ready to confront death. Matthis recognized Bartholomew, one of the mining wizards, before he even saw him.

"Master of the Death Guild," he said in a loud and almost playful mocking tone, "finally graces us."

"Let's get this done," grumbled one of the others in a voice that sounded like groans from an old timber. "Lay this poor sod to rest." The man gestured at a wooden cart. A quilt lay on top of the cart's contents but couldn't hide the outline of a man. Rafe the gravedigger leaned against the cartwheel with his arms folded, relaxed.

Matthis grunted in reply. They performed short introductions. The grizzled man was Godric. A woman who fussed over a quilt was named Nell. He pulled the solid metal hasps from their staples. The gibbet fell open down the middle. 

Nell sniffled over the cart. Matthis recognized her as a barmaid from the Staff and Flagon, but he'd never spoken to her before. They stood there and listened to the wind hiss through the trees and the chains. The undead rattled in their gibbets. A chorus of death. The three men stood with hands and arms folded. Nell clutched a shawl around her shoulders, a hand over her mouth and nose. They stood there. Not even the birds chirped.

"I suppose no one thought to call the Vicar," said Bartholomew in an uncharacteristically somber voice.

A corner of the quilt flapped onto the cart wheel, revealing a dusty black boot.

They stood there, looking at the boot and the shape under the quilt.

Nothing happened.

"Vicar doesn't like wizards," said Godric with the grizzled voice. "Probably why. Probably found someplace else to be. Probably forgot."

The main gallows beam turned gold in the sun.

They stood there, eyes on the cart. 

Matthis rubbed his neck. "Shouldn't we ... say something?"

The chains clinked in the wind. They shivered. Somewhere beyond the treeline, a raven croaked.

"Was nice to me, he was," said the maid in a steady but hollow voice. Matthis saw tear stains on her cheeks, which were soft and free from coal dust. "Came up here two months back, like most in Coalridge. Didn't want nothing from me, just a hot plate and a cup, nothing else. Didn't seem to mind that I ... Well, he talked sweetly, like I were someone special." Her voice strained. "Someone special."

Interesting, Matthis thought. Come to think of it, he had noticed a subtle difference between the old hostels and taverns and the new ones that had cropped up in recent months.

They stood there and watched the body on the cart.

"How exactly did he die?" said Rafe.

The sun crept along the gallow poles. The girl sniffed.

"It wasn't the mine that did it this time," said grizzled Godric. "It was the boy himself."

"Ah," said Bartholomew. "We wizards have to be careful with the amount of magic we use at once. Don't we?"

Godric grunted.

The wind picked up and almost tore the quilt away, but the maid yelped and snatched it at the last second. She tried to smooth it back over the dead man.

"We'd best get on with it," said Bartholomew, his voice heavy. He placed a hand on hers. She hesitated, pushed against him, tugged the corners of the quilt to cover the body. Bartholomew didn't budge. They stood there for a moment, Nell's chest heaving. Then she let go and let Bartholomew step around her. Together, the two wizards pulled back the quilt. The maid gathered it off the cart into a bundle.

"Don't use that again," said Matthis, pointing at her. "We don't know how it spreads."

She dropped the quilt. She jumped away from it and rubbed her hands in her apron. Rafe studied Matthis and looked at the quilt, hand on his chin.

"If it is contagious," Bartholomew said "you've put yourself at a very great risk. Both of you." His mocking tone had returned.

Nell whimpered.

"Leave it here," said Matthis. "I'll burn it. When this is over."

Bartholomew and Godric heaved the body out of the cart and into the open gibbet. Rafe watched with a half grimace. The maid stood by, tears on her cheeks. Matthis had expected her to leave, or at least to turn aside, but she never looked away. The iron ring fit snugly around the dead man's neck, and his legs barely fit through the bars at the bottom. The man must have been an excellent wizard, or at least well fed. They pushed the halves around the body. Matthis fastened the hasps with thick iron pins. The wizard's fingers twitched. Godric and Bartholomew swore and backed away. Nell whimpered. Matthis ignored the dead man and fastened the collar around his neck. Godric and Bartholomew stared. Nell gasped. Rafe the gravedigger simply nodded. 

It took quite a long time to pull the whole thing up to the beam with ropes, and when they got it there, Matthis climbed a ladder and hooked one of the chains hanging from the iron loop at the top of the cage onto a heavy iron spike driven into the gallows beam. He untied the hauling rope and climbed down.

They stood there so quietly that he could feel when they held their breath.

The fresh oiled metal of the new gibbet shone in the cold sun.

Another raven croaked far away in the trees.

The movement began slowly at first. It could have been mistaken for wind. The bones clacked and creaked like always. Then every skeleton moved all at once. When the commotion began, Bartholomew groaned and folded his arms. He fondled a stone he took out of his pocket, eyes downcast. Rafe leaned against the cartwheel. He looked casual, but he swallowed hard. He shifted his eyes from the gibbets to Matthis. The maid Nell yipped and turned away. The other wizard Godric bowed his head. Matthis forced himself to watch. 

Amidst the clinks of metal and the dry rustle of bone, all the skeletal remains clawed and reached toward the new corpse, their silent jaws hung open, their arms waving and scrabbling. Two of the skeletons nearest the new gibbet each seized the freshly dead man and gored chunks of flesh away. Black, congealed blood oozed from the wounds. The skeletons stuffed it between their ribs. Sometimes they smeared it all over their skulls and brown teeth. 

At first, the dead man did not move as he was torn apart. Then he uttered a long, tired groan. He made no move to protect himself.

Matthis watched the gut-churning scene carefully. He had fed them scraps of a rabbit he had snared in the woods a few weeks ago, but this was the first human flesh he had ever watched them consume. He forced himself to swallow twice. Piles formed beneath the cages where blood and globs of the dead wizard's flesh slopped to the ground. They didn't seem any more or less eager to consume this body than any animal meat he'd fed them. 

Every new bit of information could save someone's life one day. He ground his teeth. All of this had to be worth it.

"You all can leave," he said to the others. Only he had to endure this.

Long after the others left, Matthis watched the new corpse as it was slowly eaten before his eyes.